  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "41-year-old man reports a week of muffled hearing and a sensation of fullness in his left ear, starting about three days after the worst of a head cold. He denies significant pain or fever, and otoscopy is pending. The doctor is deciding whether this represents simple eustachian tube dysfunction that will resolve on its own or whether it warrants closer follow-up for persistent effusion or evolving infection.",
  "good_next_question": "Does the fullness get better when you yawn, swallow, or hold your nose and gently blow, or does it change at all when you're in an elevator or on a plane?",
  "rationale": "ETD is a mechanical, pressure-related problem, so symptoms that shift with autoinflation maneuvers (yawning, swallowing, Valsalva) or with altitude change are strong evidence that the eustachian tube itself is the issue rather than an active infection, and this pattern typically resolves conservatively with decongestants and time. If the fullness doesn't budge at all with these maneuvers, or if the ear is genuinely painful rather than just pressured, that raises concern for a persistent middle ear effusion or an evolving infection that needs otoscopy and possible antibiotics rather than reassurance. This question is more useful than asking about pain, since ETD is frequently painless, so pain presence or absence doesn't help narrow things down the way response to pressure-equalizing maneuvers does.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "eustachian_tube_dysfunction",
    "etd",
    "adult",
    "ear_fullness",
    "post_uri"
  ],
